**Verify the private key and certificate files**: Make sure they are correctly generated and match each other.
You can use tools like OpenSSL to verify the key and certificate pair.

You can use tools like OpenSSL to check the key and certificate:
```bash 
openssl rsa -in /etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/private.pem -check 
openssl x509 -in /etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/cert.pem -subject_hash 
```
Replace `/etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/private.pem` and `/etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/cert.pem` with your actual file paths.
You can use tools like OpenSSL to check the consistency of the key and certificate.

You can use tools like OpenSSL to check the files:
```bash`
openssl rsa -in /etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/private.pem -pubout -outform PEM -out public.key

openssl x509 -in /etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/cert.pem -pubkey -noout -outform PEM -out public.key.check

diff public.key public.key.check 
```
This will help you identify any differences between the two files.

You can use tools like OpenSSL to verify the key and certificate:
```
openssl rsa -in /etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/private.pem -pubout -outform PEM > public.key.pub 
openssl x509 -in /etc/nginx/certs/240110_certs/cert.pem -pubkey -noout > cert.pub 
diff public.key.pub cert.pub 
```
This command compares the public key extracted from the private key (`public.key.pub`) with the public key extracted from the certificate (`cert.pub`).
